---

Got it 👍

When you open

http://myserver/MyApp

IIS will look for a default document (e.g. Default.aspx, index.html, etc.).
Since your login page is login.aspx, IIS won’t automatically redirect there.


---

✅ Solutions

Option 1: Set login.aspx as Default Document in IIS

1. Open IIS Manager.


2. Go to your site → MyApp.


3. Double-click Default Document.


4. Add login.aspx at the top of the list.
(So when someone browses /MyApp, IIS serves login.aspx.)



👉 Easiest if your app always starts at login.aspx.


---

Option 2: Use default.aspx to Redirect

If you already have a Default.aspx (or can create one), put this inside:

// Default.aspx.cs
protected void Page_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    Response.Redirect("~/login.aspx");
}

This way, hitting /MyApp will bounce to /MyApp/login.aspx.


---

Option 3: Web.config Redirect

Add a redirect rule in Web.config:

<configuration>
  <system.webServer>
    <defaultDocument enabled="true">
      <files>
        <clear />
        <add value="login.aspx" />
      </files>
    </defaultDocument>
  </system.webServer>
</configuration>

This tells IIS that login.aspx is the default.


---

✅ Recommended: Option 3 (Web.config), because it’s clean and doesn’t require an extra redirect page.


---

Do you want me to write you a full minimal Web.config snippet (including this fix + forms auth redirect) that ensures users always get sent to login.aspx when hitting /MyApp?


